An extreme struggle: MP3 players against mobiles.
We will advise you, how to choose
While virtually every mobile can read MP3 files, no MP3 player can phone.
It seems to be clear from this that it is better to buy only one phone.
However, there are sufficient reasons to obtain an independent reader.
The choice depends entirely on the way of use and the requirements of the future owner.
It would be absurd to buy for the home a cheap gramophone of the highest quality to put on the new album by Maxim Turbulenc.
On the one hand, such musical products do not come out on vinyl disk, and, from the point of view of quality, there is no objective reason for this to happen.
Now, if there are in your shelves vinyl discs embedded, with rock art, jazz or blues, you're probably dreaming of such a gramophone.
The same is true of music during movements, namely compressed music, to say it in a simplified way - music in MP3.
There are also categories based on price and quality.
For one, it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns for one reader, just as a Pink Floyd fan would have difficulty supporting listeners purchased for twenty crowns on the market.
These are two extremes, among which there is enough room for everyone.
The choice is wide.
The lifespan of batteries is also decisive
Some high-end music readers are capable of much more than just reading music, but these are unknown functions, of course, of most mobiles.
No current device is as universal as the phone.
Besides the first functions, phone calls and SMS sending, it is able to read music and movies, record them, it has a variable-quality camera and can, for example, be used for navigation.
And if you take Smartphones and communicators into account, you'll have a small computer in your pocket.
Since no fryer can grill meat and no TV will take photographs, we are practically witnessing a miracle.
However, the universal character of the mobile is not without disadvantages.
The larger the number of functions you use, the smaller the interval between two reloads.
And the reading of music is one of the most important energy gushes.
There are few mobiles that are able to read music for ten to twelve hours, in most cases this figure is significantly lower.
In this regard, music readers (especially the most rudimentary) are significantly more performing.
In the case of cheap mobiles, count that they will only play music for a few hours.
If, in addition, you get to call it from time to time, get, to be sure, a second charge for the work - this is even valid for the more expensive devices.
The problem will not arise for MP3 players, who are capable, following a reload, of continuous operation of at least 9 hours, including the least performing ones.
Another problem occurs when recording music in the mobile.
Unfortunately, a limited part of the devices has a universal USB connector, especially since not everyone can be directly connected to the computer, without special software.
Of course, music can be recorded directly on the memory card, but few card readers can take it without a reduction, given the tiny dimensions of the memory cards used in mobile phones.
As far as readers are concerned, you do not need any software, except (iPod).
Simply fill the music device from the computer through the USB connector.
Most mobiles and readers will create themselves a media library classified according to the name of the performer, the album title, style, or then the user's judgment.
Some devices display only an index with a tree structure, in the way Windows Explorer does, others are capable of both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smart phones with operating system).
Readers are easier to handle, mobiles have more know-how
In the choice of a concrete device, you are particularly interested in the lifetime of the accumulator, the ability of memory, the quality and type of output of sound and, of course, the ease of order.
If music is for you, essentially, a background noise and if in the day you are going to listen to it only for a limited time, for example by taking the tram, you are enough for any mobile reading MP3.
Almost all mobiles are capable of this today.
You don't even have to pay too much attention to the music formats that the mobile or player is capable of reading.
All are able to read the MP3 and the vast majority of the music that will reach you will have exactly this format.
It is one of the most common formats and apart from it, the vast majority of the devices can also read from the WMA music format.
The AAC (format used by Apple firm and its iPods) is less common.
High-end mobiles also enable, for example, the purchase of online music.
Just visit, from the mobile phone, the corresponding operator's web pages (or other provider's) and buy the song or album in question.
This service alone should be a compelling reason for obtaining a musical piece of furniture.
The supply of operators is unfortunately miserable and is, in most cases, limited to fast-made radio tubes.
The prices are not the lowest either.
However, it is generally considered that this way of buying music (whether through GSM, the Internet, or even through the wireless Internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always wear their cell phones on their own.
Every time you want to listen to something, you just have to get out of your pocket, while you forgot your MP3 player at home.
However, it is also important if you always have on you listeners or a handlesfree with connection.
If this is not the case, you can use the built-in enclosures, which have virtually all mobile phones, but a minimum of MP3 players.
For many, the main advantage of musical furniture is their price.
The cheapest normally costs less than three thousand.
For a prize of three four thousand crowns, you can have a walkman already very convenient.
In most cases, however, you will be constrained by the absence of an outlet for ordinary listeners.
The price of the best phones and the best tools, also provided with an entry for ordinary listeners, does not exceed fifteen thousand.
Readers, on the other hand, have the advantage of having an easy order.
Really anyone can assure the order of the most rudimentary readers - who do not necessarily correspond to the least expensive (cf. our choice).
A minimum of functions; and the similarity of the order with that of a cassette post, commonly used in the past, or a gramophone, is obvious.
There is no risk of collision in the form of a randomly connected mobile internet, followed by a huge data transmission bill.
Which device to choose
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. the Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for interchangeable memory cards (type M2, microSD, and so on).
Even taking into account the additional purchase of such a card, you will not exceed two thousand crowns.
But be careful.
Basic models in principle only support cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB.
Only the most expensive ones get out even with 8 GB memory cards.
If you already own a mobile phone and still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, take a Cowon, a Creative, a Sony, a Samsung, an Emgeton, or an iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you don't have to spend more than 1,100 crowns.
If you are one of the most demanding listeners, choose specialized walkman mobiles (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices are equipped with independent control keys for MP3, and this is how easy the control is to approach that of an independent MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson, whose walkman series mobile phones have the same user menu as MP3 players sold separately, is the one that went as far in this field.
The same service, in the same price category, but with a memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and a lifetime of the accumulator (usually 15 hours, up to 35 hours) higher, is provided by an MP3 player produced by one of the above mentioned brands.
A first virtual operator will win the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The mobile market in Czech Republic is relatively advanced, with our operators offering virtually the same services as their partners in Western Europe.
Despite this, we still lack something - a virtual operator, which would force conventional operators to lower prices.
Maybe he won't be missing for a long time.
We have already mentioned, on many occasions, the fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
The ČTÚ (Czech Telecommunications Office), which reported that the price of an SMS was higher than in the rest of the Union, has also confirmed it.
As a result of the last steps taken by the European Commission in the area of the regulation of roaming charges, a paradoxical situation is likely to occur - the SMS sent from abroad will be for some customers of Czech mobile operators less expensive than in the country.
How is it possible that prices in Czech Republic remain so high, compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that would really want to get into the fight.
This may seem paradoxical, as we still have three mobile networks and a penetration that far exceeds 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this regard, Pavel Dvořák, the President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTú), said several times that in Czechia there was no place for another operator, chorused with operators.
It is probably true that a classical operator with its own network apparently has no more luck (in fact, now it will only find frequencies).
However, there is still a possibility - a virtual operator.
It is precisely the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that has led to a considerable fall in prices, which should subsequently also be reacted to by conventional operators.
Yet, before the entry of the trouble parties such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile into the market, voices similar to those we hear today at home were heard in Britain.
However, it appeared that there was still room for such operators and that they could have a real success.
We do not have to go too far to find examples.
In February we had informed you of the launch in Poland of the virtual operator Mobilking.
In just six months, this operator managed to win more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth operator in the country.
Let's add that behind Mobilking, there is the financial group Penta, which owns among others the U:phone in Czech.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility of focusing on a much more concrete target group.
In order for their operation to be effective, they actually need much less customers than a classic operator.
They are, in fact, free of relatively high building, operating and maintenance costs for the mobile network.
Thus, in the world, virtual operators profile themselves as low-cost operators - they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often offset by a limited service offer.
For example, in Britain, Tesco Mobile offers SMS at least twice as expensive as its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, putting on an unusual target group can also be a good publicity shot.
In fact, this operator specifically targets men.
"Real men choose Mobilking - an operator they like and can trust," says David Seibert, the CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, operating this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say, if such a concept would be likely to work with us as well.
Miroslav Čepický, the spokesperson for Vodafone, doubtless: "The Czech market is relatively small for a segmental approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
As much as it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the supply of services."
In Czech Republic, no chance, mobile operators say
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual operator in Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are discussing the expansion of this project successfully, but negotiations in Czech Republic are not very encouraging.
The launch of Mobilking will instead take place in other countries in our area," said a telephone interview for Mobil.cz Jana Studničková, spokesman for the Penta financial group.
It has thus indirectly confirmed that the Czech operators were not in any event in favour of this idea.
On the contrary, they are trying to make every effort to ensure that a potential competitor cannot appear.
The GTS Novera group, which would like to take a new step to become a real competitor of Telefonika in the business customer field, has not, for a long time, concealed its intention to launch a virtual mobile operator.
"We want to be able to offer our customers not only fixed telecommunications services, but also mobile.
And the sooner the better.
We have already conducted negotiations on this possibility on several occasions with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of us, we have been able to move forward in the negotiations," said Pavel Kaidl spokeswoman.
The future is therefore perhaps promising.
According to informal information, it seems that we may be able to host the first virtual operator by the end of the year.
But for the moment, its creation is accompanied by total silence.
"At the moment, we do not believe that there is a place on the Czech market for a virtual operator as such.
The Czech market is compared with others very specific.
For the time being, no subject with a complex and serious project in this area has contacted us," said Vlastimil Sršeň of the press department of Telefonika O2, in his statement for Mobil.cz.
Other operators also refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokesperson Martina Kemrová says in a rare agreement with the O2 statement: "We have not registered for now a viable and bilaterally beneficial project, which could serve as a basis."
And she adds: "It is practically excluded that a virtual operator would appear in the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
In order to operate in such a limited period of time, we should now have a concrete agreement."
Instead, Vodafone directs his attention to the fulfilment of requests to obtain his own 3G licence.
Miroslav Čepický says in relation to this: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and especially in the area of shared costs and infrastructure.
This, in our opinion, means the most input from the customer's point of view.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is the discovery of a partner to establish a common network for a fast mobile internet."
The authorities responsible: in line with the operators
The approach of mobile operators is easily understandable, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would have led to a fall in prices and thus a decrease in their profit.
So what good is it to facilitate the advent of such a competitor?
When it comes to their interests, the operators know how to hear how to lanterns at the fair. Chicane accompanying the creation of the U:fon also demonstrates it.
The greatest apparent pressure on the ČTU, at the time of the creation of the U:fon, was that exerted by the company T-Mobile.
This information is available to the public from the ČTÚ web pages.
Now, today, the U:fon is willing to use as an argument not to accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová noted: "Competition in the mobile market has been further increased recently by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile operator.
Given the nature of the mobile market in RT, it is obvious that the entry of an additional player would subject it, and especially its services, to high requirements."
But given the attitude of the mobile operators here, the indifference of Czech regulators seems disconcerting.
However, this is not just the attitude of ČTÚ, which, unlike Britain and other developed countries, unfortunately does not have the power to intervene in economic competition in Chechnya.
It belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (UOHS).
In view of this problem, the latter adopts its typical position.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible following the conclusion of an agreement between a mobile operator and the virtual operator in question concerning the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such agreement has been reached at this time, as the offer of potential stakeholders has not previously brought sufficient interest to conventional operators," said Kristián Chalupa, UOHS's Department of External Relations, in response to our question.
Such a statement would not surprise the representatives of the operators.
But on the part of an office, which must represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, take care that no one takes advantage of its position on the market, such a statement is more than confusing.
Especially since Kristián Chalupa adds: "Foreigners, where virtual operators are normally present, it can be seen that their entry into the market has contributed to lower prices of mobile telephone services."
However, exerting pressure in the direction of an honest functioning of the market and a fall in prices is apparently not part of the UOHS' interests.
What is indeed shocking is the almost touching agreement of the three mobile operators, which derives from their reactions.
The question, if it really is a chance, arises naturally.
In the same way, a gasoline price that is strictly identical to all service stations is probably due to the chance and hard fight of competition.
"The Office has not noted any signs of anticompetitive behaviour in this regard, so it has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position, therefore none has a corresponding increased responsibility for their behaviour on the market.
The tools needed to open the mobile market for virtual operators are probably missing even from the telecommunications regulator," said Chalopa.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of the many points of discord.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by ČTÚ, according to which, from the point of view of economic competition, telecommunications constitute a single market.
None of the Czech operators has a dominant position on such a market.
However, some legal experts propose another vision of things: for the creation of a virtual operator to be possible, the consent of the network operator must be obtained each time.
And the mobile operator has quite logically the monopoly on its network.
This is why he necessarily plays a dominant role in a certain segment of his activity.
However, even without admitting this argument, it should be at least worrying for the UOHS that three mobile operators conduct visibly in a similar manner.
However, complaints from many stakeholders (including GTS Novera, already mentioned) show that they face similar constraints in negotiations with all operators.
Resuming responsibility for ČTÚ is a fairly common turn in communications, through which ÚOHS washes the hands of the case.
We have already encountered this kind of attitude in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, the recent introduction of the Telecommunications Act, a broadening of ČTU's powers in the area of economic competition in telecommunications, was not successful, although many experts promised that the situation would be improved.
That is why the representatives of the UOHS must know very well, but their interests are apparently elsewhere.
When no one looks, it can work.
However, the operation of a kind of pseudo-virtual operators, several in the Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies publishing their own list of prices for mobile telephone services, but the latter are only partly public.
In most cases, there are companies involved in multi-level marketing.
Specialized mobile phone services are offered, for example, by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The price lists of these firms generally only reach elected members.
The magic tower consists of the fact that the company does in front of the operator is a classic company client, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, it obtains special price offers (and others).
What is problematic is that the trading conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such a resale.
"If what you're talking about was going to happen, it could be a breach of the contractual conditions that we would consider and which could lead to a halt in collaboration with the company in question," Martina Kemrová answered our question.
However, it is quite unlikely that an echo of such activity would have been achieved even to those responsible for mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three companies mentioned it can be thousands of customers.
One operator, however, does not rule against such a procedure.
Indeed, the activities of these companies bring non-negligible profits, and at the same time, as opposed to genuine virtual operators, they do not threaten them at all with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický indicates the possible problems: "The law allows such speculations, however, the services of these companies are used only by a negligible percentage of customers.
In addition, they are forced to admit that the SIM card in their phone is not registered under their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it, in the way of ordinary mobile operators."
That is precisely what should seem strange to ČTU.
In addition, another question is raised at UOHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes to such a procedure, why do they block the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that ÚOHS has relatively broad powers to be able to disclose such activity, and if it does not wish to confine itself to explanations from operators, who claim to have no idea that this would occur, their contractual conditions forbidding it.
When we will no longer be the most expensive country
As we have already mentioned on several occasions, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has led to a considerable decline in the price of services.
However, almost in all countries where virtual operators appeared, conventional operators were endeavouring, sometimes more or less, to prevent their creation.
The arguments used by the latter were practically the same - a market too small, even too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
However, it is precisely at this level that regulators have intervened in developed countries, not in the interests of mobile operators, but of their customers.
Both by formal measures and by informal pressure, they have eventually achieved the creation of a first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators address this issue in the form of a hot potato that is disposed of by transmitting it to a close target.
As a result of the experiences we have, we cannot get rid of the impression that confusion in their skills is more than profitable in these cases.
But let's not touch it after the cognée.
If the background information says true and a virtual operator will soon appear at home, the Czech mobile market may be moving back.
If one of the operators has accepted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, the UOHS can hardly remain impassable in the face of the rejection (to discrimination) of other interested parties.
And perhaps we will stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
