You can listen to the four new versions on the iHNed.cz server.
Bělohlávek views Czech national chant as one of the most beautiful hymns.
As he had previously entrusted to Český rozhlas (Czech public radio), he chose for the interpretation of the solo versions of the singers with young and representative voices, which are marked and appreciated.
"Since the beginning, I was trying to take care that both singers and the choir have a good word, so that we can understand the words, that they sing simultaneously," he said.
The Czech national anthem will celebrate its 175th anniversary next year.
For the first time in 1834 Kde domov mðj resounded on the boards of Stavovské divadlo (the State Theatre) in Fidlovačka (Kermesse des satetiers), an original Czech piece by Josef Kajetán Tyl, accompanied by the music of František Škroup.
It has become popular and people have spontaneously made it appropriate.
After the creation of Czechoslovakia in 1918, the first couple naturally became an integral part of the national anthem.
It remained one of the seven national symbols even after the creation of the independent Czech Republic.
