The Southeasts called for a referendum in the USA
In 1945, the Germans of the Southeast called for Šumava to be integrated into the United States.
This is the result of a letter from the collections of Jihočeská vědecká knihovna (The Scientific Library of Southern Bohemia).
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we want at least to live under the patronage of the United States of America.
In 1945, some groups of South Germans allegedly approached the President of the USA with such a desire.
This is due, among other things, to a letter kept in a private archive, which is now deposited in the collections of the Jihočeská vědecká knihovna.
Germans from Český Krumlov asked in the letter the American President not to allow "šumavská župa" (a region of forests south of Bohemia) - annexed by Hitler under the Munich agreement - to be returned to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation well and want to be truly sure that the words proclaiming that the American troops come to the territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," is written in the letter, "People, to whom the fate of Šumava stands."
Since the Czechoslovakia rally is supposedly promising - knowing the Czech national character - that of brutality, attitude without regard, misunderstanding, oppression and servitude, the authors of the letter ask the American President to take in his hands the protectorate of Šumava for now and forever.
"We cannot believe that you would grant this territory to a foreign state to us, which oppresses and destroys minorities and has contributed nothing to the victory of the Allies without taking into account the opinion of the quarter of a million inhabitants," is written in the letter.
The alleged reason why the authors cannot sign the letter is the fear of the desire for revenge of the "Czech oppressors".
If the president of the USA doubted the opinion of the Germans of Šumava, he would have to organize, according to the authors of the letter, a referendum in the region to determine whether his inhabitants wanted to be part of the USA, or to live under the patronage of the United States.
Although the text contained in the letter may, in view of the current knowledge of the post-war history, appear somewhat naive, according to some survivors, it illustrates well the expectations of the Germans of the Southeast of the time.
While the Czech Germans had to at least consider that the question of their expulsion from the Republic would arise, very few of them were given such an opportunity.
Some expected the United States and Great Britain to obtain a certain type of autonomy for the Southeasts.
Others believed that they would simply remain in Czechoslovakia.
The famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, born in České Budějovice, confirms this.
During the war, he was, as German of České Budějovice, engaged in the navy in the Baltic countries.
When, at the end of the war, he was captured by the English and placed in the capture camp of Holstein, dozens of Czech Germans came to see him for learning the Czech.
"They believed that once they returned home, the Czech would benefit them," said Chalupa.
None of the captured Germans who lived in Czechoslovakia before the war believed that, following the Beneš Decrees, he would be expelled from the republic.
You do not think — you pay!
An emotional campaign will attack the drivers
The most expensive road safety action in Czech history.
One way to characterize the emotional media campaign is to launch the Ministry of Transport on Wednesday.
Minister Aleš Žebíček's office believes that it will discourage drivers from driving dangerous behaviour.
This campaign costing 150 million will appear on television, radio, cinema, internet, but also on leaflets.
It should discourage drivers from driving fast and alcohol on the wheel.
But also remind them to take the belt before starting.
It wants to touch the consciousness of young drivers, bikers, pedestrians, not to mention professional drivers.
What will appear in the spots?
Especially personal stories that will attack emotions.
It also bears witness to the "blooding" slogan of the entire campaign:
You do not think — you pay!
The phrase "Don't Think" is capitalized on the license plate.
Then, in a flash of blood, there's the phrase "You'll Pay."
Which must mean that one can pay for life for a moment of carelessness.
Spots will "hunter" spectators until 2010.
The ministry was inspired by similar campaigns in Anglo-Saxon countries, where images are commonly seen with drastic images of the victims of accidents.
It believes that this will lead to a reduction in the accident rate and the number of deaths on Czech roads.
The spots were prepared by the Euro RSCG agency.
Sugar and whipping strategy against drivers
"What works with the drivers is the sugar and whip system.
For them, sugar is represented, for example, by gaining time, when they grill a red light.
The whip is the threat of a fine or an accident.
The risks must be reminded of the drivers," says Martin Kořán, the transport psychologist at Na Homolce Hospital.
This is how we need information campaigns in the press and, above all, negative advertisements, the psychologist believes.
The signs indicating the danger to drivers are, in his view, already less effective.
"When a static panel warns against a danger is installed, it will probably quickly merge with the environment and the drivers will no longer notice it," Kořán said.
