Rats also have sensations
Does a rat or a cockroach run away from the danger, does that mean he's also suffering from fear?
Neurophysician Joseph LeDoux is convinced of this: many animals also have sensations.
But how can we verify that he feels the same when he behaves in the same way as we do?
In the "Edge" online magazine, contributions have been published for several years by famous scientists.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents in a series of articles of the answers to the question "What do you think is true without being able to have proof of it?"
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else having so far been able to prove it just as one cannot prove that other human beings have a consciousness.
But in that case, we can at least hope that all human brains will have the same configuration.
As soon as we turn to other species and address the questions of the feeling or in general of consciousness, we enter hard-to-do terrain because the hardware does not match.
When a rat is in front of a danger, he does the same thing as many other animals: he kills, flees or attacks.
Human beings behave the same way, which is why some scientists deduct from it a comparable subjective experience.
However, I do not believe in it.
Two aspects of the brain structure make the transposition of our subjective life to that of difficult animals.
One aspect is that the circuits associated almost always with human consciousness include the prefrontal lateral cortex (because of its participation in short-term memory and in the functions of direction and execution).
This vast region is much more developed in humans than in other primates and appears to be completely absent in other beings.
So at least for these aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal Cortex, among which the consciousness of who we are, and the ability to predict and decide, it is reasonable to assume that the human being differs even from the other primates.
Another significant particularity could be found in the linguistic nature of Man: a large part of his existence is related to language, which often means that his consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even if consciousness was not to depend on language, it would surely influence it, so that the animal consciousness, whatever the way it is produced, would probably differ much from most of our states of consciousness.
That is why it is so difficult to determine what consciousness can look like in other animals.
If this, internal and subjective, does not leave itself to be measured or, because of this particular hardware, analyze based on our own experience, then its observation poses major problems.
Most of my developments refer to the contents of the conscious experience, but there is another aspect of consciousness that should be more readily accessible scientifically.
Animal consciousness processes could be examined regardless of their content, and that is exactly what happened in studies on short-term memory of primates, especially with the example of visualization.
