"I photograph the master outside the scene to capture elements of his character" Günther Bauer - Photographer
No heels, no sneeze clothes.
The essence of the masters of flamenco, freed from all tensions to obtain the relaxed appearance of man or woman.
On the one hand, the artist.
On the other hand, the person.
Inseparable except in intimacy, in these unknown moments of the general public, where one discovers intimate gestures and the stolen glances of artists who do not care to get on stage.
German Günther Bauer mixes in "Flamenco - people" the theatricality of some plays with singers, dancers and guitarists with this less known side of artists.
In this project, the photographer takes over the specific iconography of flamenco from different angles.
Included in the programming of the Flemish Photography Month, the exhibition "reflects the international importance of flamenco, greater every day", explains the creator, who clarifies that "Flamenco - people" "may be anyone but, after seeing the photos, the observer realizes that these are not typical images of artists on stage.
These people photographed "on the street" are artists capable of transmitting on stage of passion, sadness, joy...by captivating the public.
To capture moments of personality of these artists you don't have to take pictures on stage.
They have a personality and a clean character.
What interests me was to create an intimate atmosphere that allows me to capture with the camera the moments of personality of flamenco stars."
With the festival "Chant Popular des Mines", Bauer began a long journey in 1997 to photograph singers, guitarists or dancers with a plate camera.
These are portraits that, thanks to the choice of camera and material, recall classical photography.
The implementation of different stylistic means breaks with the classic side of the image, giving it a touch of modernity, this reflects the flamenco perception according to Bauer: "A music with very traditional roots that evolves and surprises every day".
It is not about dance or singing in itself, but about the personality and character of the artist who captures the public with his art.
The search for essentials and magic was the constant of this work presented to the El Fotómata gallery these days.
The flamenco celebrities such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, are part of the selection made from about sixty artists photographed.
The project was transformed into an anthology of flamenco, which will soon be published in a collection book of portraits exhibited at the gallery.
The passion for Bauer's portraits led him to repeat the idea two years ago with the "Portraits de old sportifs" ("SportARTproject").
Although the concepts are different in "Flamenco - people", the photographer admits that he loves to photograph the portrait of people, know them and be able to enter their lives for a longer or longer moment.
I believe that portrait is the most difficult kind in photography.
You're in front of people, people that sometimes you don't know or just leave you for a few minutes so you can take a picture of them.
Despite these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to make my ideas come true."
This collection of portraits of the current flamenco entitled "Flamenco - people", is exhibited at Galerie El Fotómata, located on the 20th Street of the Mata (a street parallel to the Peupleraia d'Hercule) which will be open until October 16.
