According to statistics, between 30% and 75% of motorists arrested for driving more than once in drunkenness are taking back the car.
Alcoholock would avoid this because it is a vehicle-connected system that measures the alcohol rate in the breath and prevents the vehicle from starting if the driver does not breathe before; or when the driver's alcohol rate is higher than that authorized.
Its cost is more than 1,000 euros and is borne by the driver.
In this regard, a study conducted in the United States in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with this device had reduced up to 65 per cent of the offences during the first year of installation.
And in Spain it is estimated that this could save 115 people each year.
This measure is based on administrative sanctions for two reasons: dealing with these behaviours before they become criminal offences.
And facilitate its implementation, since legal reform can be done by ordinary means, but reform by criminal means requires reform of the organic law.
The device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial form, although some industrial and functional vehicles already have one on an experimental basis.
