The first time this happens, it can surprise you, but actually it doesn't matter.
It is a benign alteration in sleep that is called sleepiness.
This is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
It's certain there's more than one talking at night.
This phenomenon can appear in a very sporadic way (once in life, for example, associated with a severe fever episode), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once a month ...), the day according to the child does not remember anything anymore.
There are no single causes that determine its appearance
They are often related to other sleep disturbances such as nightmares, night terrors, night enuresies (piping in bed) or sleepwalking, but this is not always the case.
As we have said before, they can also be associated with very strong fevers, stress or overexcitation.
However, it is a little studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it occurs is also very variable.
He may speak with a quiet little voice, with isolated words, whispers or on the contrary with screams, weepings, long speeches ...
In the event that sleepiness becomes very common, it would be wise to observe the child and consult a specialist, to check if there is a problem that causes much anxiety and to get an explanation of this problem.
We have said that this is a benign alteration, that is why there is no treatment, unless it is related to another alteration in sleep that can be treated (for example, if it is related to sleep apnea or stress).
What can be done is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child before going to sleep.
So look for quiet games and avoid more or less violent TV shows or shows.
With very nervous children and having difficulty relaxing, relaxation techniques can be used to help them calm themselves internally.
This will allow the child to have a more peaceful sleep.
As soon as the sleeping nets appear, try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will no longer remember what happened.
Useful advice
Don't wake him.
It's useless because he's unconscious and you'd wake him up.
Even if he speaks, he sleeps and rests.
Remember that if it is very distressed several times, it is advisable to consult a doctor or check what causes so much anxiety in the child.
If you understand what he says (which is not usual), do not have the temptation to question him for information.
You won't get anything, because by sleeping, he's not conscious so he can organize his thinking.
In addition, you will hear what he says, but you will not know what he is dreaming of, from the moment you pay attention to the way you interpret the information and the conclusions you draw from it.
Never tell the child that you can question him at night to know his secrets.
Not even joking.
This causes much anxiety.
In conclusion, don't worry, it's nothing bad, it's an episode that only lasts a few minutes.
