Interview - Blood is safe again
Héma-Québec was celebrating the 10th anniversary of her foundation yesterday, and her president, Dr. Francine Décary, was right to rejoice because Héma-Québec became one of the most secure and effective blood suppliers in the world.
And above all, he regained the public's confidence that had been seriously shaken by the blood scandal contaminated in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, the national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were contaminated by the acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this drama and the public gulf, in February 1994 the Government of Canada instituted a public inquiry, chaired by J. Horace Krever, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations for the recurrence of such a disaster.
While Judge Krever was slow to file his report, some provinces then set up a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gelineau Committee fulfilled this mandate.
Following the Gelineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were established in Canada: Hema-Québec to serve Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all other provinces and territories.
"In 1998, when Hema-Québec started his activities, barely 38% of people still trusted the blood system in Quebec," recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
Through efforts to improve the safety of blood products and work on the ground during the years that followed, we regained public confidence," she said before proudly asserting that at the beginning of 2008, almost 94% of the Quebec population now had confidence in Héma-Québec.
However, Dr. Décary keeps in mind that "confidence is something extremely fragile."
Hema-Québec applied the precautionary principle from its inception on 28 September 1998.
At that time, many cases of the human form of crazy cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease, had been erupted in Europe, telling the one who held the fort since its foundation in 1998.
"And we didn't know at all if this disease could be transmitted by blood.
One of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gelineau reports was that when one does not know and that a serious disease can result from it, namely Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease, which is characterized by degeneration of the brain inevitably leading to death, exclusion measures were introduced.
In April 1999, the blood of people who had stayed in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980 was refused.
A few years ago, however, it was shown beyond doubt that this disease was transmitted by blood.
This episode has shown us that the precautionary principle that has been applied has meaning."
In 1999 a much more sensitive technique of HIV testing appeared on the market: nucleic acid (TAN) tests that directly detect in donor blood the presence of the virus itself and not that of antibodies against the virus, on which the tests used until then rested.
TANs have shortened the silent period, which extends between the time the person was infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, says the specialist.
This period could be reduced to less than one week.
This significantly reduced the risk of certain donors being infected without knowledge and not being able to detect them.
These improvements have significantly lowered the risk of contracting AIDS through blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people is at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
"In other words, it means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone gets infected with HIV.
As Hema-Québec distributes every year between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products, it will take more than 24 years before a case of transmission of HIV by a blood product occurs.
I believe that today you can feel comfortable receiving or prescribing blood transfusion to recover health," says Hema-Québec's head of management.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
We never know what pathogen will emerge in the system.
No later than last year the Chikungunya virus appeared on Réunion Island, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We must be constantly vigilant," Dr. Décary continued before stressing that, in addition to a security supply, Hema-Québec must also provide for a sufficient supply.
"Needs are increasing because the population is aging.
Since anticancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need a red blood cell or platelet recharge.
The ageing of the population also has consequences for the blood donor network, which on average only accounts for 3% of Quebecers eligible for blood donation."
Any healthy person, aged 18 and over who meets the eligibility criteria, may, however, give blood every 56 days, six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who offer their blood are not accepted, because they are affected by AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have travelled to a country where malaria persists, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
"With these 3%, we manage to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
The shortages are very rare.
But it is necessary to renew the members of this donor network as they age and can no longer give their blood.
It is difficult to convince people to give their blood, but above all to retain them and encourage them to become a regular donor.
Today's life is so scary, we rarely find the time to spend an hour giving of its blood," says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Québec provides not only blood products but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that are almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Hema-Québec, which also manages the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was already considered a biomedical waste grunts with a blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the banking of our thousandth sample of cord blood and are expected to take more than a thousand per year.
It should start to be proposed for transplants early next year," says Dr. Décary, who describes this cord blood collection program as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed that they have no access to it," as Hema-Québec does not have the means to propose this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
