While it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth that they judge, especially in the case of defamation prosecutions, but the law.
Without any surprise, this fundamental difference is completely concealed by Mr. Garver.
Because, for Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate would be to lead to the ruin of anyone who dares to support a position contrary to his own?
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the authors and editor of the book Black Canada will have to spend considerable sums to prepare their defence and fight, with very uneven weapons, against an army of lawyers supported by the almost bottomless pockets of mining.
The tactic, in these unequal struggles, is often to ruin the defendants in order to impose a friendly settlement that will haunt the opposition in addition to frightening anyone who dares to consider the matter again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it was in the public opinion that she should have presented her view of the facts.
Contrary to what is happening in many of the countries where Barrick Gold is working, discussions in Canada are normally done through the exchange of ideas and not through the coup d'étrage.
It was therefore sufficient for the mining industry to open its books, records and to establish a real debate, through newspapers, the media, publications and the financing of independent research teams that could have made light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold seems not to trust public opinion and rejects petitions and letters of support to Black Canada authors.
Perhaps Mr. Garver could explain how he can at the same time ask for a "public" debate while scorning the opinions of the same audience?
In the vice president's world, it seems that this word refers only to paid lawyers and not all Canadians; this is a rather narrow view of the concept.
In democracy, even the detractors have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold doesn't understand - or doesn't want to understand - is that the public who supports the authors and publishers of Black Canada is doing it first and foremost because it rejects the brutal way in which it is mining.
This audience is ready to hear Barrick and judge, but on the basis of civilized exchanges of arguments, and not in the context of what many perceive as a bail-out (continuing the "public debate", Barrick Gold has just filed a formal complaint with Black Canada authors, intimidating them to cease the use of this term...).
Beyond Mr. Garver's surreal speech, Barrick Gold's prosecution is a direct attack on university research freedom and the quest for truth, essential to any democratic society.
It denies, as a whole, the right to citation of credible sources and debate on facts and interpretations, which are the very basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible to study and discuss issues that displease the rich companies of this world in a country like Canada, who can do so, without repeated prosecution?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could do so in accordance with the scientific standards used by Black Canada authors.
She has a right of reply.
The academic environment, to which we belong, has long been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's excessive pursuit clearly shows that, contrary to what she claims, she does not want a transparent debate.
It is a loss to the academic world, as it is to the public debate in Canada, and it is time that governments put in place mechanisms that limit this kind of abusive prosecution.
Wall Street Rescue Operation - Democrats and Republicans
The Bush administration and the leaders of Congress, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the largest economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the 700 billion US dollars plan to halt the financial crisis that has shaken Wall Street for months has yet to be endorsed by both Houses of Congress.
In particular, it provides for better control by the elected of its implementation, new mechanisms to ensure the reimbursement of public money committed, new provisions to contain the number of houses seized for default payment, as well as a right to look at wages paid to the leaders of the companies rescued.
The US Secretary to the Treasury, Henry Paulson, the Speaker of the House of Representatives, Nancy Pelosi, and the Republican representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight yesterday, at the end of a two-day negotiating marathon.
"We have made great progress towards an agreement that will be effective in the markets," said Bush administration representative Henry Paulson.
"Everything has been done to protect the real economy and ordinary Americans from the current Wall Street crisis," the Democrat explained.
"That's the fundamental point: if we don't do this, trauma, chaos and disturbances on the daily lives of Americans will be immense," Republican Judd Gregg said.
Negotiations had turned sprint in recent hours because of fear of the effect that would cause a new failure on investor mood.
The deadline was to open the markets this morning.
The two candidates for the U.S. presidential election, later associated with the negotiations, were rather in favour of the agreement, but did not fail to express their discontent with the fact that they were forced to reach this end.
The Democratic Senator Barack Obama attributed himself to the addition of certain provisions to the agreement, including the provision to allow owners to keep their homes and the provision on the salaries of government-recovered business leaders.
"When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of some, there is no welcome.
But these measures are needed," he commented on the American television waves.
Asked on another channel to find out if he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, replied, "I'd like to see the details, but I hope so."
"The broad lines that I have read [present] that this is something that we will all have to digest and with which we will be able to move forward.
The option of doing nothing is simply unacceptable," he said.
The 700 billion plan aims to buy with taxpayers' money the doubtful, risky and unsoldable debts of US financial institutions.
It comes after 14 months of a crisis triggered by the outbreak of a real estate bubble that initially led to the collapse of mortgages at risk (subprime) before extending to other more widespread forms of credit securities (PCAAs) and resulting in liquidity freezes and bank and financial institutions.
It was a group of Republican elites who had the first draft of agreement capped last week.
This impasse has been believed to have been removed since the Democrats accepted that certain "toxic" assets of companies in difficulty are only provided by the government, rather than purchased.
In order to round things up for everyone in Congress, we also added a provision stipulating that if the government were to take up losses for five years with this program, it could put in place new taxes to help it recover its implementation.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first tranche of 250 billion to be added to another 100 billion if the President deems it necessary.
The payment of another 350 billion should be endorsed by another vote of Congress.
In exchange for its assistance, Washington will obtain participation in the aided companies that will be worth dividends in case of profit and that it will be able to resell when the torment is passed.
The federal government will be able to delay the seizure procedures for housing related to the real estate loans involved in this plan, as well as to set limits on the pay and severance allowances paid to the leaders of the affected companies.
The architects of the plan would like to see him put to the vote of the House of Representatives as of today, and of the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all their efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will have the green light.
In fact, voices continued to rise against this project yesterday, both in the Republican and Democrat camp.
"Of course, Washington doesn't hear you," Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House's Finance Committee, told his constituents.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But not the one that is to take advantage of the taxpayers."
Animator of a small group at the Congress called "the caucus of skeptics", Democratic representative Brad Sherman presented things differently, but came to the same conclusion.
"Four hundred distinguished professors of economics, including three Nobel Prizes, wrote to us to tell us: we are asking Congress not to hurry and examine carefully the way to go," he said yesterday.
At the same time, in Europe, we once again had proof of the global nature of the crisis.
At the end of an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalisation of the Fortis banking group for EUR 11.2 billion (US$ 16.3 billion).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg had been made necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it had renounced its full-fledged competitor since it lost EUR 2 billion (US$ 2.9 billion) in the crisis of risk-based real estate loans in the United States.
Fortis employs 85,000 people and is one of the twenty largest European banks and ten largest insurers.
"This is not money lost," Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said yesterday.
In exchange, voting rights are collected in the bank and influence.
It is precisely something that savers and households now appreciate that time is uncertain."
Meanwhile, on the other side of the Channel, the British government seemed to be in the process of nationalizing another bank damaged by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government would take over all outstanding loans from Bradford and Bringley Bank, including over 41 billion (75.5 billion US) of real estate loans.
Yesterday, the Spanish bank Santander announced that it would buy the branches and customer accounts of the British bank.
Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank, after Northern Rock, that the British government should nationalize since the beginning of this financial crisis.
