The psychology of superpower: Why do we spend more money?
During auctions, buyers tend to spend more, and to overestimate the merchandise.
Neurology and economic researchers at the University of New York have been able to update the neurological and economic bases of this known and apparently irrational behavior.
According to their study published in the journal Science, humans do not want to be detached in this type of competition, such as an auction sale on eBay, and that is why they even prefer to pay too high a price.
These researches have attempted to develop a neurological pattern of this kind of "game" using sales to experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played the loto, while the other group participated in a playful auction, while using a functional magnetic resonance (FRI) process, researchers analyzed the active brain domains of experimental subjects.
In both games, participants could earn money, but during the auction, which is an essential element of a third, the whole being under the brain stem, called striatum, was moving in an intensive way when the part was lost.
This part of the brain, along with several other functions, plays a role in the "self-stimulation" mechanism of the nervous system.
Therefore, according to the researchers, the rise in prices is explained by the leak in the face of the violent reaction of striatum.
In support of their theories, the economists of this group of researchers continued financial surveillance analyses.
In these cases, three groups were overemphasized in the face of a partner, in various circumstances.
They simply informed the group about the actual value of the product in question, and so did they.
To another group, they promised that if, in addition, they won the game, then they would receive an additional $15 in reward.
While the third group received this $15 before the auctions, members of the group also lost that money, in case they lost the auctions.
The difference between these two groups is in fact that the emphasis was placed at one on victory, while at the other on failure.
By proving the hypothesis of neurologists, the players' team members "against failure" were willing to put higher stakes than those made by the control group and the "for victory" group.
"These results cannot be demonstrated by any existing economic theory.
In fact, each of them only explained the phenomena found during auctions only by the pleasure of winning and the parade in front of the risk.
Only neurological imaging methods have helped to eliminate the contradiction between the two theories by leading, now, to a third explanation." - noted Andrew Schotter, Professor of the Faculty of Economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should we consult a doctor?
In the world, about half a billion people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary, chronic liver disease is mentioned among the leading causes of death.
It is estimated that one hundred miles of patients carrying the hepatitis virus in Hungary, but only seven miles after treatment, which is due to the fact that patients often do not know that they are carriers of the virus.
The name hepatitis is a generic name given to infections affecting the liver and caused by different viruses.
There are many similarities between their symptoms. Inflammation of the liver and jaundice are characteristic, but pathogens and diseases caused differ from one another.
Hepatitis viruses, according to pathogens, spread mainly in two forms: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tube (e.g. contaminated food or water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses through the blood and organic liquids (sperm, vaginal secretion, saliva).
For travellers, it is recommended that they get vaccinated against A and B viruses. There is no vaccine against C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after the consumption of contaminated foods, in general, accompanied by poor general condition, weakness, stomach ailments and nausea.
Then it develops on the skin and on the white of the eye a visible yellowish, the saddles become clearer and the urine takes a darker color. Healing can take two to three weeks.
Throughout the world, every year a million people die of the most serious form of this pathology, such as liver cancer or cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason is that, according to estimates, only one in ten patients receive medical treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: if it is not treated, it can lead to cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most patients do not know how to reach the virus, because the pathogen sneezes the liver cells. In many cases, the first symptoms appear only after 20-30 years.
Therefore, early prevention is very important, as well as regular screening tests.
Contamination is much higher than average among a population of three groups: people who underwent blood transfusion before 1991, drug users and tattoos.
Currently, there are 200 million patients with chronic hepatitis C worldwide.
Since the disease can be detected by a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult your doctor as soon as symptoms of unknown origin are observed.
The disease can be cured, if detected on time. The virus can be eradicated from the body, thus the risk of contamination disappears and the development of cancer is prevented.
September 30 is the World Hepatitis Day, organized for the first time in 2004 by organizations representing the sick around the world.
Its objective is to draw attention to chronic liver cirrhosis caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
Does he who believes in God feel less pain?
According to the results of a recent research, religious belief would function as a sort of analgesic, which would have already contributed to making the death of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
The British daily Telegraph published an article that researchers at the University of Oxford carried out an interesting experience by analyzing at what level belief in God could influence tolerance to the pain of the human being.
As part of this experience for the least bizarre, 12 Catholic believers and so many atheists were subjected to electroshock, while each of them observed a painting representing the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude much of the suffering.
Thanks to a technique of palpation of the human brain, it was also found that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain responsible for regulating pain.
This analysis is the first of a series of experiences, to which academics, scholars, philosophers and theologians participate from different sectors of the university.
More specifically, the experiment is carried out in the following way: an instrument emitting sparks and spreading electroshock is fixed to the left hand of the experimental subject.
The researchers asked the participants of the experience to look at two paintings in a sustained manner, one being the Virgin Mary painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century and the other, the Lady with hermine painted by Léonard de Vinci in the 15th century.
The researchers at the origin of this experience hoped that the view of the Virgin Mary evokes a kind of state of faith among believers, while the choice of Da Vinci's painting, not very different from the first, dealt with its soothing effect.
Experimental subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, and during that time received 20 electroshocks in four successive parts, while looking at either religious-themed painting or the one with a more general theme.
Catholics said that in the sight of the Virgin Mary, they felt like "safe", like someone whose "care" they "kept" and who "resolved themselves, and peace invaded them".
In view of religious theme painting, they reported 12% pain less than when they looked at Léonard's work.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who himself has taken part in the experience, thinks that one can achieve the same effects with any other strong image, in the atheists, provided that one finds the right photo.
"We should find an image against which they react very positively, such as a mother or father," the psychologist said.
Tom Wright, Anglican Bishop, welcomed the results of these researches.
"The practice of faith should change and in many cases change our personality," Wright added.
After these excellent results, the question of what would be the effect on the regulation of the pain of the subjects if one showed believers a Madone painted by Leonardo or by a painter of the same caliber?
Would the view of a better quality Virgin Mary produce better results?
