Smart automobile mimics bourdon flight
What better method would be to develop technologies capable of avoiding an obstacle, if not the imitation of an existing obstacle detector already in nature?
For example, bees.
In the amazing project presented at CEATEC, taking place in Japan, the burgeoning bees gave the strategic idea of departure to the engineers at Nissan to inspire them on how they should design the next generation of obstacle detectors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan built a mini robot car, a bio-inspired auto-robotized, BR23C-type control system, which he has equipped bee qualities, the ultimate goal being to encourage the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
During its flights, each bee constitutes its own space, oval-shaped, which actually looks a lot like our safe protection helmet - explained, during the exhibition, Kazuhhiro Doi, the director of the research and development department and technological public relations of the brand.
The bee's facetted eye plays an important role, since it is able to see in all directions, in a 300 degree angle.
In order to imitate the functions of the facetted eye, the engineers approached the idea of laser telemeter.
It identifies the obstacles in an angle of 180 degrees and at a distance of 2 meters in front of the BR23C, it evaluates the distances and sends a signal to the microprocessor, which transforms it into a avoidance maneuver immediately.
The perception of the obstacle takes place in a fraction of a second. Then, the mini auto robot, mimicking the movements of the bee, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning it from an angle sufficient to avoid collision.
Contrary to any existing system at present, this avoidance exercise is carried out entirely instinctively.
"If this was not the case, the mini auto robot could not react quickly enough to avoid the obstacle" - explains Toshiyuki Andoh, the director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robotic car project.
It must react instinctively and instantaneously, since this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and innermost layer of the protective envelope, a layer where for the moment the collision is considered inevitable.
This whole process must reflect what bee does to avoid other bees.
The process must take place in a blinking eye.
Unlike bees, the difference cannot go up, down or diagonally, it can only be two dimensions, and only in the direction in which the wheels can rotate.
In this way, instead of the infinite combinations that bees possess to avoid other bees, in our case, only the rotating movement, acceleration and slowing as maneuvers at the disposal of the mini auto robot could be used.
The BR23C uses polymer lithium batteries that are lighter and whose energy concentrate is greater, making their lifespan longer than in the Lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, it is the intelligent instinctive reaction that is paramount, not data processing, and even less the ability to store.
This mechanism should deal with only a few incoming signals per second, and respond to them.
It is not necessary to store them and to react with intuitive logic based on the data of previous manoeuvres. In this way, it uses only a few dozen kilo-bytes of continuous memory.
You don't need memory of a giga-bytes capacity, or even mega-bytes.
This is the first step towards designing a technology used for instant avoidance. Nissan's estimates suggest that this system will make its entry into cars manufactured in series in the next ten years.
Another application could be its incorporation into the GPS satellite navigation system, so that it can guide the driver to its destination by avoiding obstacles on its way.
