Industrial prices continued to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 per cent compared to the previous month, and by 12.9 per cent compared to the August 2007 month - the Central Statistical Office of Hungary reports.
Industrial export sales prices increased 1.1 per cent compared to July 2008, compared to those of a year earlier, decreased by 3.9 per cent.
As a result of domestic and export price fluctuations, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 per cent compared to the previous month and by 3.2 per cent compared to the previous year.
Domestic industrial sales prices only increased to a lesser extent: 0.1 per cent compared to the previous month.
Domestic sales prices in the processing industry were only slightly up 0.1 per cent compared to July.
In August 2008, the most significant price increase was observed in the leather and footwear manufacturing sector (2.8 per cent), with first, the manufacture of bags and belts with a monthly increase of 4.6 per cent, then the production of shoes with 2.5 per cent monthly increase.
The higher prices of plastic and chemical raw materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the product and chemical manufacturing sector (1.6 per cent).
A deflation resulted in oil processing (1.4 per cent), machinery and electrical equipment (0.9%), as well as a minimal increase in wood processing (0.1 per cent).
Paper production, publishing and printing prices have not changed.
Other sectors of the processing industry recorded an increase of between 0.2 per cent and 0.9 per cent.
In the electricity, gas, steam and water sectors, which are a significant weight in domestic industrial exploitation, prices have risen by 0.3% in August, mainly due to the effect of the increase in gas prices introduced by the authorities since 1 July.
In a 12-month comparison, taking into account the domestic sales of the processing sectors, oil processing prices were the most significant increase (32.4 per cent).
In the manufacture of metallurgical products, prices increased by 13.2 per cent, while in the important area of food production, beverages and tobacco, prices increased by 11 per cent.
Price reductions occurred in the textile and textile production sectors (2.5 per cent), as well as in the manufacturing of electrical machinery and appliances (0.3 per cent).
In the other sectors of the processing industry, the price increase has evolved from 0.6% to 9.1%.
In the whole processing industry, prices increased by 10.2 per cent over the past year.
The prices of the electricity, gas, steam and water sectors exceeded 18.7 per cent in the previous year.
Among the domestic trade groups and sectoral allocations, in August, the most significant monthly price increase (0.7%) was initiating investment profit sectors.
In the consumer goods sectors, prices increased by 0.3 per cent, while those in the energy and material sectors for further processing did not experience any change compared to the previous month.
In August 2008, compared with the same month of the previous year, the largest increase in energy and material production was observed for further processing (16.8 per cent).
In the consumer goods sectors, inflation of 6.8 per cent was measured, while in the profit-initiating sectors, inflation of 1.4 per cent was measured.
The export sales prices of the industrial sector in HUF increased by 1.1 percent in August compared to the previous month, while they decreased by 3.9 percent over 12 months.
In one month, our national means of payment declined by 1.7% compared to the euro, and 7.1% compared to the dollar. Compared to August 2007, it increased by 7.5% compared to the euro and 15.9% compared to the dollar.
