Mp3 player pointed to the finger, they risk hearing.
Listening to full volume music over an extended period using portable music devices such as Mp3 players can cause permanent hearing injuries.
This is what the European Commission announces, which, in a press release in Brussels, quotes the opinion of the Scientific Committee, on the unexpected and recently identified health risks (Csseri) of the EU, published today.
"of this scientific report- lisons us in the note- it shows that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to full-volume music using portable musical devices, for more than one hour per day and per week, risk a permanent loss of auditory capacity."
"I am concerned that such a large number of young people who frequently use portable music devices and full-volume mobile phones can unconsciously damage their hearing in an irreparable manner," says Meglena Kuneva.
"According to the scientific data, the EU responsible is pursuing a clear risk and we must react quickly.
What is most important is to raise consumer awareness and make this information public.
We must also review existing control systems in view of scientific opinion so that they are fully effective and can follow the new technologies."
Brussels has asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the intensive use of portable musical devices and the increase in the number of young people exposed to the noise they generate.
"Scientists-concluded the EU executive- confirm that there are good reasons to be concerned, and that the European Commission will now examine with the Member States and other interested parties, what measures could possibly be taken to better protect children and adolescents, against noise exposure from portable musical devices and similar devices.
There is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable music devices to 100Db, but the concern increases as to the hearing damage that could result from excessive exposure to such noise sources.
It is possible to limit these data by using solutions such as reducing noise levels and exposure duration.
The EU Scientific Committee notes that users of portable music devices, which listen to full-volume music (more than 89 decibels) for 5 hours per week, exceed the limits currently in force for the maximum level of noise at the workplace.
Those who listen to music under such conditions for extended periods of time risk a permanent loss of hearing capacity after 5 years.
This affects 5-10% of the users of these devices, and their number can be quantified to about 2.5 and 10 million people in the U.E.
