The elites in danger.
The phenomenon had already occurred a few days ago, with the vote of the House of Representatives, contrary to the $700 billion rescue plan approved by the White House: a significant number of Americans were, and is still, more interested in punishing Wall Street than in saving the American economy.
And it is the New York Times yesterday that confirms it by communicating that the current crisis divides the Republican Party, even more divided between its long-standing, moderate East Coast soul, favourable to the federal institutions and to the business community, and its new soul, on the contrary, conservative, hostile to "the Washingtons" and to the world of finance, powerful especially in the Central and South states.
The soul, quite rightly, which has made itself felt despotically with the vote that I was speaking to you at the beginning.
What has just been cited, however, is only one example of the changes, of the major changes that the economic earthquake in progress is pre-announced or already leaves to run: not only in the United States, but throughout the West, and may not only be here.
In the United States as in Europe, the crisis seems to speed up the phenomenon that has been under way for some time, to the extent that, in the new climate, they are solidifying and revealing themselves.
The first of these phenomena is the revival, the extraordinary revival, of the double-class sovereign state, compared to a kind of renationalization of the economy.
The crisis is indeed a crisis of banking and financial institutions which, of course, have close relations with abroad, but which, above all, are involved on a large scale, the balances of people and families living in one country, in one state.
This immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: that is to say how to respond to the difficulties and protests of people and families who are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears economically global but politically, it is almost national.
Political internationalisation seems really out of play or, it has little to say: the obvious evidence is provided to us by the European Union, which, shared as usual, between the various interests and between the various national strategies, cannot decide any common policy lines.
And so, it is the government of each state that everyone expects interventions, rescue and recovery plans, new rules, and above all a affection for credits: when we go through a difficult period, there are only those states that have economic resources, the mass of financial resources that can try to put things back in place.
They also have the necessary means and legitimacy to use them: two resources of invaluable value, elements that no market or international organization can ever have in a similar way.
This new emphasis on the state-nation crisis is in perfect harmony with the ever-increasing importance that the most recent economic developments in the economy tend to attribute to a factor quite related to this element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, while we were convinced that we were now entering the realm of the network, of the increasingly sophisticated technology, of the non-material, convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we realized once and for all that our future will have to settle its accounts more and more with things that are relatively unmaterial such as water, crops, oil.
Things that can certainly be transported from one place to another from the earth, but that are absolutely linked to a circumscribed space, to a territory.
Thus, who is sovereign, certainly has more maps than the one who is not, that is, the one who has the bad luck to live in a place without harvest, without oil and without water.
I now come to the second novelty which, however, foresees a fracture.
Who says Territory, State, Government, inevitably says Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this regard, the economic crisis appears to produce two convergent phenomena.
On the one hand, the awareness of the objective need for authoritarian leadership, the search for a person who knows how to take over the situation.
On the other side, a wave of discredit for existing leadership, economic species that have proved inadequate and full of shadow.
And in addition, something still deeper, in a certain sense, even worrying: a discredit, a suffering, an image of inadequacy, a sense of remoteness that tends to involve the entire class of directors in an increasing number of Western countries.
This increases the conviction of the various classes, before the actions are the same ideas of the social elites until now at their peak, their way of listening and being, their culture in the complex acceptance of the term, to have at the same time, and to be ever more alien to the opinions of the majority.
in short, the demand for leadership, subterranean food, a powerful and ramified movement of delegitimizations of the ruling classes and traditional political orders, which manifest themselves in the "revolts" improvised elections or, in the changes of collective moods of the latter most recently, from the conservative ascension in Austria Bavaria, at the fall of the Labourers in Britain, to the rebellion of the American congressmen against Bush (and it could well be that the victory of the right in Italy did not come by chance).
