Students who are victims of expensive rents, up to 900 euros for one room.
The student rental market does not know about crisis
According to the last survey of the Sunia, the tenants' union, renting a single room can cost a student, up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples, 600 in Rome.
"The phenomenon has now reached very serious aspects to the point of excluding entire categories of young people, from the right to study because of the very high overall costs that the families from which they come must support - explains the head of the study office in Sunia, Laura Mariani- in these cities, the strong demand on the part of the students has so distorted the market that a generalized growth process has begun for the residents themselves.
In most cases, rental offers also contain a series of violations: free, unregistered, rent-free contracts, sub-locations.
For Sunia, extraordinary interventions through the revision of tax are necessary to calm prices.
Reading in detail the survey, we see that in Milan, for a bed in the Brianza area, it takes about 450 euros; for a single room, it goes from 650 euros minimum (Black Band area), to an average value of 800 (Lambiate area, Udine, and Fiera) to a maximum of 900 euros (Vittoria area)
In Florence, an average bed costs 350/400 euros, one room about 700 euros.
In Bologna, where students concentrate in the nearby areas of the University, it takes 250/280 euros for a bed in a double, and from 370 to 500 for a single room.
In Rome, in areas close to central universities (San Lorenzo, Piazza Bologna), about 600 euros are required for a single, 450 for a double bed.
Values slightly lower (550 euros for a single) for areas close to other Universities (Ostiense and Cinecittà).
You can save only if you go away in the peripheral areas: 300 euros for a bed, and 450 for a single in the area Predestina, Centocelle or similar.
In Naples, for a bed it takes 300/400 euros, for a simple one, we spend 400 to 600 euros, with higher prices in the Policlinico, Vomero, and Colli Aminei areas.
In Bari, for bed, you have to count 250/350 euros, at least 350 for a single.
In smaller cities, prices are lower in absolute terms, but they are of major importance in the city's economy.
Finally, cities such as Perugia, where rents are often taken by extra-Community students, there is a subsequent anomaly: the rent requested from foreign students is increased by 25/30% compared to that applied to Italians.
Farewell old Paradise cinema, the cities elicit the historic halls.
Historical cinemas ferment in favor of the Multiplexes.
"A city without cinema halls is a blind city, it's like a face without eyes"
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore, illustrates what is happening in the major Italian urban centres, but also in the cities of the province,
The process of marginalizing cinemas, with the birth on the outskirts of large multi-halls, and the death of consumption of the mono-rooms in the central areas of the cities, is one of the major events that we find inevitable and indisputable; it also has all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
To disappear, they are often historic places full of memory, "it is as if one of my friends disappeared, someone we know, with whom we shared a piece of path and so many emotions" observes the director of the New Heaven Cinema, a film that offers to Tornatore 20 years ago, the first Oscar as well as the Grand Prix of the Cannes Jury, and that told the poetry of a provincial hall, and the nostalgia in a way to live the cinema, lost can be forever.
The figures provided by Anec, the main association of merchants, mean everything: in the last five years, 316 traditional cinemas have closed, and these are the halls of the main cities that have paid for it mainly: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the areas most affected by the closure, Emilia Romaine is in the lead with 82 cinemas single rooms lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
The evidence confirms that the first responsible for their disappearance is the advent of multiplex, because it is well the three Italian regions that have recorded the most new multi-salle cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany as in Emilia-Romagna.
"Italian exploitation has developed irrationally" observes Paolo Protti, President of the Anec, "it is useful to build new structures, but it should nevertheless guarantee the survival of those already existing, because when a room closes in a city, these frequenters are not necessarily all willing to go to multiplexes.
Not to mention the lack of deliberation of credit for traders: the state's previous debt is about 10 million euros.
It is shameful that, from an ethical and moral point of view, the Government does not respect existing laws.
To support the sector, EUR 16 million to EUR 18 million per year would be required.
Let us note the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that, worried about these closures, has decided to resolve the situation thanks to the signing of a protocol between Mairie and Anec, the first of these in Italy, to defend and promote the single cinemas rooms of the historic centres and on the outskirts.
Among the regulations, there are tax facilitation measures for managers and benefits to the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the restricted traffic area, and will have special rates for parking and some parking.
"It's an initiative that I like" notes Giuseppe Tornatore "and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna setting up other measures.
It is clear, however, that, in order to contrast the superpower of multiplexes, traditional rooms must also improve the quality of sound and image, because today's audience is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that for me has always been important: the closure of the Bagheria Supercinema, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make "New Paradise cinema" that I had thought for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass in front of the Rialto, or the Quirinal de Via Nazionale, now closed, where I have experienced so many shared emotions, I turn from the other side so as not to see the black signs by the dust.
